    <h1>Summary of Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) Chapter</h1>

    <h2>1. Classes and Objects</h2>
    <p>- <strong>Class:</strong> Blueprint for objects.</p>
    <p>- <strong>Object:</strong> Instance of a class containing data (properties) and behavior (methods).</p>
    <pre><code class="language-csharp">
// Example
public class Dog { public string Name; public void Bark() { Console.WriteLine($"{Name} barks!"); } }
Dog myDog = new Dog(); myDog.Name = "Buddy"; myDog.Bark();
    </code></pre>

    <h2>2. Constructors</h2>
    <p>- Special methods used to initialize objects when they are created.</p>
    <pre><code class="language-csharp">
// Example
public class Person
{
    public string Name;
    public Person(string name) { Name = name; }
}
Person p = new Person("Alice");
    </code></pre>

    <h2>3. Encapsulation</h2>
    <p>- Protects object data by using <code>private</code> fields and <code>public</code> getters/setters.</p>
    <pre><code class="language-csharp">
// Example
public class BankAccount
{
    private double balance;
    public void Deposit(double amount) { balance += amount; }
    public double GetBalance() { return balance; }
}
    </code></pre>

    <h2>4. Polymorphism</h2>
    <p>- Allows objects to take many forms via method overloading and overriding.</p>
    <pre><code class="language-csharp">
// Overloading
Calculator c = new Calculator();
c.Add(2,3); c.Add(2.5,3.5);
// Overriding
Animal myAnimal = new Dog(); myAnimal.MakeSound(); // Bark!
    </code></pre>

    <h2>5. Abstraction</h2>
    <p>- Hides complex implementation and exposes only essential features using <code>abstract</code> classes or interfaces.</p>
    <pre><code class="language-csharp">
public abstract class Shape { public abstract void Draw(); }
public class Circle : Shape { public override void Draw() { Console.WriteLine("Draw Circle"); } }
    </code></pre>

    <h2>6. Interfaces</h2>
    <p>- Define a contract that classes must implement.</p>
    <pre><code class="language-csharp">
public interface IVehicle { void StartEngine(); }
public class Car : IVehicle { public void StartEngine() { Console.WriteLine("Car engine started"); } }
    </code></pre>

    <h2>7. Static, Readonly, and Const</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Static:</strong> Belongs to the class, shared by all instances.</li>
        <li><strong>Readonly:</strong> Assigned once at runtime in constructor or declaration.</li>
        <li><strong>Const:</strong> Compile-time constant that cannot change.</li>
    </ul>

